The paper deals with shifts of sequences and their properties, which are typically studied in the area of discrete mathematics and theoretical computer science. The concept of sofic-Dyck shifts is related to context-free languages, which falls under the category of formal languages (cs.FL). The paper also discusses the zeta function of these shifts, which is a topic in dynamical systems (cs.DS) and information theory (cs.IT). The use of visibly pushdown languages suggests a connection to automata theory and formal languages (cs.FL), while the study of shifts of sequences can also be related to symbolic dynamics (cs.SY) and logic (cs.LO).
